Explanation

✅ 1. TF‑IDF (Document → Importance Calculation)
🔹 What you did
You gave multiple sentences → system converted them into numbers.

🔹 Step-by-step understanding


Input (Raw Text)

Example: “I love cricket”
Each sentence = document



Tokenization (breaking text into words)
I | love | cricket



Vocabulary creation

Combine all unique words:

cricket, football, sports, love



Term Frequency (TF)

Counts how many times a word appears in a document
Example:

love → appears 1 time in each doc



Inverse Document Frequency (IDF)

Checks how rare a word is across all documents
Formula idea:

IDF ↑ if word appears in fewer documents
IDF ↓ if word appears everywhere



TF × IDF

Final importance score




🔹 Final Logic
Common word → low score (love)
Rare word → high score (cricket, football)


✅ ✅ ✅ 2. Word2Vec (Context-based Learning)
🔹 What you did
You gave word pairs like:
doctor → hospital
nurse → hospital


🔹 Step-by-step understanding


Input format

List of words grouped as sentences



Context window

Model looks around a word
Example:

doctor ↔ hospital (related)



Training process

Neural network learns:

words appearing together → similar vectors



Vector creation

Each word → list of numbers

doctor → [0.2, -0.5, ...]



Similarity calculation

Uses cosine similarity
Checks angle between vectors




🔹 Final Logic
Same context → high similarity
Different context → low similarity


✅ ✅ ✅ 3. GloVe (Global Relationships)
🔹 What you did
You loaded a huge file where:
word → vector


🔹 Step-by-step understanding


File structure
doctor 0.123 0.456 ...



Reading file

One line at a time



Splitting
first word → key
rest numbers → vector



Storage
dictionary: word → vector




🔹 Difference from Word2Vec
Word2VecGloVeLocal contextGlobal co-occurrenceLearns from sentencesLearns from full corpus

🔹 Final Logic
Similar meaning → similar vectors


✅ ✅ ✅ 4. Embedding Layer (PyTorch)
🔹 What you did
You created:
nn.Embedding(10, 5)


🔹 Step-by-step understanding


10
→ Number of words (vocabulary size)


5
→ Features per word




Input

index = 0


Output

vector of size 5


🔹 Internally
It is just a lookup table


🔹 Final Logic
Word index → vector representation


✅ ✅ ✅ 5. Cosine Similarity
🔹 What you did
You compared two vectors

🔹 Step-by-step understanding

Two vectors

v1 and v2



Dot product
→ measures alignment


Magnitude
→ length of vectors




Final formula

cosθ = (A · B) / (|A||B|)


🔹 Meaning of results
ValueMeaning1Same direction0No relation-1Opposite

🔹 Final Logic
Higher value → more similar


✅ ✅ ✅ 6. Text Classification
🔹 What you did
You trained model to classify:
good → positive
bad → negative


🔹 Step-by-step understanding

Text input

good movie
bad movie



Vectorization
→ Convert text into numbers (word counts)


Training
→ Model learns:


good → positive
bad → negative


Testing
→ New sentence:

excellent movie


Prediction
→ Model assigns label


🔹 Final Logic
Pattern learning → classification


✅ ✅ ✅ 7. Self‑Attention / Transformer
🔹 What you wrote

Query
Key
Value


🔹 Step-by-step understanding


Query
→ what we are searching for


Key
→ what is available


Value
→ actual information




Matching

Query compares with all Keys


Weighted output
→ produces final representation


🔹 Final Logic
Focus on important words


✅ ✅ ✅ 8. Transfer Learning
🔹 What you did

Loaded pretrained model
Replaced final layer


🔹 Understanding

Model already trained on:

ImageNet (huge dataset)


You change last layer:

1000 classes → 2 classes


🔹 Final Logic
Reuse knowledge → adapt to new task


✅ ✅ ✅ 9. Fine‑Tuning
🔹 What you did

Freeze all layers
Unfreeze some layers


🔹 Understanding

Lower layers → general features
Last layers → specific features


🔹 Final Logic
Train deeper layers for better accuracy


